# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The **American Chemical Society** (**ACS**) is a scientific society based in the United States that supports scientific inquiry in the field of chemistry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Founded in 1876 at New York University, the ACS currently has more than 262,000 members at all degree levels and in all fields of chemistry, chemical engineering, and related fields.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] It is one of the world's largest scientific societies by membership.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization and holds a congressional charter under Title 36 of the United States Code.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Its headquarters are located in Washington, D.C., and it has a large concentration of staff in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a source of scientific information through its peer-reviewed scientific journals, national conferences, and the Chemical Abstracts Service.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Its publications division produces over 90 scholarly journals including the prestigious *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, as well as the weekly trade magazine *Chemical & Engineering News*.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS holds national meetings twice a year covering the complete field of chemistry and also holds smaller conferences concentrating on specific chemical fields or geographic regions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The primary source of income of the ACS is the Chemical Abstracts Service, a provider of chemical databases worldwide.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS has student chapters in virtually every major university in the United States and outside the United States as well.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] These student chapters mainly focus on volunteering opportunities, career development, and the discussion of student and faculty research.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The organization also publishes textbooks, administers several national chemistry awards, provides grants for scientific research, and supports various educational and outreach activities.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In 1874, a group of American chemists gathered at the Joseph Priestley House to mark the 100th anniversary of Priestley's discovery of oxygen.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Two years later, on April 6, 1876, during a meeting of chemists at the University of the City of New York (now New York University) the American Chemical Society was founded.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The society received its charter of incorporation from the State of New York in 1877.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Although Chandler was a likely choice to become the society's first president because of his role in organizing the society, New York University chemistry professor John William Draper was elected as the first president of the society because of his national reputation.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Draper was a photochemist and pioneering photographer who had produced one of the first photographic portraits in 1840.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Chandler would later serve as president in 1881 and 1889.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In the ACS logo, originally designed in the early 20th century by Tiffany's Jewelers and used since 1909, a stylized symbol of a kaliapparat is used.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The *Journal of the American Chemical Society* was founded in 1879 to publish original chemical research.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] It was the first journal published by ACS and is still the society's flagship peer-reviewed publication.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In 1907, Chemical Abstracts was established as a separate journal (it previously appeared within JACS), which later became the Chemical Abstracts Service, a division of ACS that provides chemical information to researchers and others worldwide.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] *Chemical & Engineering News* is a weekly trade magazine that has been published by ACS since 1923.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The society adopted a new constitution aimed at nationalizing the organization in 1890.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In 1905, the American Chemical Society moved from New York City to Washington, D.C.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] ACS was reincorporated under a congressional charter in 1937.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Congress and signed by president Franklin D.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] ACS's headquarters moved to its current location in downtown Washington in 1941.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] ACS first established technical divisions in 1908 to foster the exchange of information among scientists who work in particular fields of chemistry or professional interests.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Divisional activities include organizing technical sessions at ACS meetings, publishing books and resources, administering awards and lectureships, and conducting other events.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The original five divisions were 1) organic chemistry, 2) industrial chemists and chemical engineers, 3) agricultural and food chemistry, 4) fertilizer chemistry, and 5) physical and inorganic chemistry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, there are 32 technical divisions of ACS.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] This is the largest division of the Society.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] It marked its 100th anniversary in 2008.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The first Chair of the Division was Edward Curtis Franklin.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The Organic Division played a part in establishing Organic Syntheses, Inc. and Organic Reactions, Inc. and it maintains close ties to both organizations.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The symposia also honor national award winners, including the Arthur C.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Cope Award, Cope Scholar Award, James Flack Norris Award in Physical Organic Chemistry, Herbert C.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Brown Award for Creative Research in Synthetic Methods.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The Division helps to organize symposia at the international meeting called Pacifichem and it organizes the biennial National Organic Chemistry Symposium (NOS) which highlights recent advances in organic chemistry and hosts the Roger Adams Award address.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The Division also organizes corporate sponsorships to provide fellowships for PhD students and undergraduates.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] It also organizes the Graduate Research Symposium and manages award and travel grant programs for undergraduates.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Local sections were authorized in 1890 and are autonomous units of the American Chemical Society.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] They elect their own officers and select representatives to the national ACS organization.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Local sections also provide professional development opportunities for members, organize community outreach events, offer awards, and conduct other business.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The Rhode Island Section was the first local section of ACS, organized in 1891.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] There are currently 186 local sections of the American Chemical Society in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] International Chemical Sciences Chapters allow ACS members outside of the U.S. to organize locally for professional and scientific exchange.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] There are currently 36 International Chemical Sciences Chapters.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] ACS states that it offers teacher training to support the professional development of science teachers so they can better present chemistry in the classroom, foster the scientific curiosity of our nation's youth and encourage future generations to pursue scientific careers.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] As of 2009, Clifford and Kathryn Hach donated $33 million to ACS, to continue the work of the Hach Scientific Foundation in supporting high school chemistry teaching.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The Society sponsors the United States National Chemistry Olympiad (USNCO), a contest used to select the four-member team that represents the United States at the International Chemistry Olympiad (IChO).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS Division of Chemical Education provides standardized tests for various subfields of chemistry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The two most commonly used tests are the undergraduate-level tests for general and organic chemistry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Each of these tests consists of 70 multiple-choice questions, and gives students 110 minutes to complete the exam.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS also approves certified undergraduate programs in chemistry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] A student who completes the required laboratory and course work—sometimes in excess of what a particular college may require for its Bachelor's degree—is considered by the Society to be well trained for professional work.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS coordinates two annual public awareness campaigns, National Chemistry Week and Chemists Celebrate Earth Week, as part of its educational outreach.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Since 1978 and 2003 respectively, the campaigns have been celebrated with a yearly theme, such as "Chemistry Colors Our World" (2015) and "Energy: Now and Forever!" (2013).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The GCI was founded in 1997 as an independent non-profit organization, by chemists Joe Breen and Dennis Hjeresen in cooperation with the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The Petroleum Research Fund (PRF) is an endowment fund administered by the ACS that supports advanced education and fundamental research in the petroleum and fossil fuel fields at non-profit institutions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Several categories of grants are offered for various career levels and institutions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The fund awarded more than $25 million in grants in 2007.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The PRF traces its origins to the acquisition of the Universal Oil Products laboratory by a consortium of oil companies in 1931.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The companies established a trust fund, The Petroleum Research Fund, in 1944 to prevent antitrust litigation tied to their UOP assets.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS was named the beneficiary of the trust.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The first grants from the PRF were awarded in 1954.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In 2000, the trust was transferred to the ACS.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS established The American Chemical Society Petroleum Research Fund and the previous trust was dissolved.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The PRF trust was valued at $144.7 million in December 2014.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS International Activities is the birthplace of the ACS International Center, an online resource for scientists and engineers looking to study abroad or explore an international career or internship.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The site houses information on hundreds of scholarships and grants related to all levels of experience to promote scientific mobility of researchers and practitioners in STEM fields.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The Society grants membership to undergraduates as student members provided they can pay the $25 yearly dues.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Any university may start its own ACS Student Chapter and receive benefits of undergraduate participation in regional conferences and discounts on ACS publications.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The American Chemical Society administers 64 national awards, medals and prizes based on scientific contributions at various career levels that promote achievement across the chemical sciences.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS national awards program began in 1922 with the establishment of the Priestley Medal, the highest award offered by the ACS, which is given for distinguished services to chemistry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Additional awards are offered by divisions, local sections and other bodies of ACS.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Nichols Medal Award was the first ACS award to honor outstanding researchers in the field of chemistry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] It was established in 1903 by the ACS New York Section and is named for William H.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Nichols, an American chemist and businessman and one of the original founders of ACS.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Of the over 100 Nichols Medalists, 16 have subsequently been awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The Willard Gibbs Award, granted by the ACS Chicago Section, was established in 1910 in honor of Josiah Willard Gibbs, the Yale University professor who formulated the phase rule.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The Georgia Local Section of ACS has awarded the Herty Medal since 1933 recognizing outstanding chemists who have significantly contributed to their chosen fields.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] All chemists in academic, government, or industrial laboratories who have been residing in the southeastern United States for at least 10 years are eligible.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The New York Section of ACS also gives Leadership Awards.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The Leadership Awards are the highest honors given by the Chemical Marketing and Economic Group of ACS NY since December 6, 2012.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] They are presented to leaders of industry, investments, and other sectors, for their contributions to science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) initiatives.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Roy Vagelos (Regeneron, Merck), Thomas M.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Connelly (DuPont) and Juan Pablo del Valle (Mexichem).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS also administers regional awards presented annually at regional meetings.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Ann Nalley Regional Award for Volunteer Service to the American Chemical Society, Regional Awards for Excellence in High School Teaching, and the Stanley C.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] Israel Regional Award for Advancing Diversity in the Chemical Sciences.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] ACS Publications is the publishing division of the ACS.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] It is a nonprofit academic publisher of scientific journals covering various fields of chemistry and related sciences.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In addition to academic journals, ACS Publications also publishes *Chemical & Engineering News*, a weekly trade magazine covering news in the chemical profession, *inChemistry*, a magazine for undergraduate students, and *ChemMatters*, a magazine for high school students and teachers.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] However it has recently launched new open access journals and provided authors with open access publishing options.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In 2006, Congress debated legislation that would have instructed the National Institutes of Health (NIH) to require all investigators it funded to submit copies of final, peer-reviewed journal articles to PubMed Central, a free-access digital repository it operates, within 12 months of publication.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] At the time the American Association of Publishers (of which ACS is a member) hired a public relations firm to counter the open access movement.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In spite of publishers' opposition, the PubMed Central legislation was passed in December 2007 and became effective in 2008.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] As the open access issue has continued to evolve, so too has the ACS's position.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS has also introduced several open access publishing options for its journals, including providing authors the option to pay an upfront fee to enable free online access to their articles.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In 2015, the ACS launched the first fully open access journal in the society's history, *ACS Central Science*.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS states that the journal offers the same peer-review standards as its subscription journals, but without publishing charges to either authors or readers.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] A second open access title, *ACS Omega*, an interdisciplinary mega journal, launched in 2016.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In 2005, the ACS was criticized for opposing the creation of PubChem, which is an open access chemical database developed by the NIH's National Center for Biotechnology Information.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS raised concerns that the publicly supported PubChem database would duplicate and unfairly compete with their existing fee-based Chemical Abstracts Service and argued that the database should only present data created by the Molecular Libraries Screening Center initiative of the NIH.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS lobbied members of the United States Congress to rein in PubChem and hired outside lobbying firms to try to persuade congressional members, the NIH, and the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) against establishing a publicly funded database.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS was unsuccessful, and as of 2012 PubChem is the world's largest free chemical database.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS is also the only provider of a major scientific publication database (SciFinder) that imposes a restriction on the number of records that can be exported.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] None of the competing products, such as Web of Science (owned by Clarivate), Scopus (owned by Elsevier) and The Lens (owned by Cambia) have similar restrictions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS has been involved in numerous lawsuits regarding access to its databases, trademark rights, and copyrighted material.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In many of these cases, the ACS lost or ended up with an unenforceable judgement.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS was also found guilty in several lawsuits brought against the Society by its employees.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] In 2004, a group of ACS members criticized the compensation of former executive director and chief executive officer John Crum, whose total salary, expenses, and bonuses for 2002 was reported to be $767,834.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] The ACS defended the figure, saying that it was in line with that of comparable organizations, including for-profit publishers.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, two employees were reported to have a total compensation exceeding $900,000, while 694 had a compensation exceeding $100,000.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The **American Society for Mass Spectrometry** (**ASMS**) is a professional association based in the United States that supports the scientific field of mass spectrometry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] As of 2018, the society had approximately 10,000 members primarily from the US, but also from around the world.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The society holds a large annual meeting, typically in late May or early June as well as other topical conferences and workshops.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The society publishes the Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The Society recognizes achievements and promotes academic research through four annual awards.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] Fenn Award for a Distinguished Contribution in Mass Spectrometry both are awarded in recognition of singular achievements or contributions in fundamental or applied mass spectrometry, with the Biemann Medal being focused on individuals who are early in their careers.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] Hites Award is awarded for outstanding original research demonstrated in papers published in the Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The Research Awards are given to young scientists in mass spectrometry, based on the evaluation of their proposed research.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The Fellows of ASMS are awarded to individuals in recognition for their scientific contribution to mass spectrometry and for their contribution to the ASMS community.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The Society holds an annual conference in late May or early June as well as topical conferences (at Asilomar State Beach in California and Sanibel Island, Florida) and a fall workshop, which is also focused on a single topic.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/american-society-for-mass-spectrometry] Conferences on Mass Spectrometry and Allied Topics have been held yearly since 1953.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] The **Association of Greek Chemists** (Greek: Ένωση Ελλήνων Χημικών, ΕΕΧ) is the chemical society of Greek chemists.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] The Association of Greek Chemists is a public legal entity that reports to the Ministry of Industry, Energy and Technology.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] Its headquarters are in Athens: 27 Kaniggos Street, 10682, Ethans, Greece.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] It was founded in 1924 in order to act as the Greek government's official advisor on Chemistry related issues.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] Chemistry has been taught in Greece as a category of natural sciences since the 19th century.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] In 1837, chemistry was taught in universities by the Bavarian Dr Lanterer, and later by Al.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] The first public analytical laboratory was founded in Lesbos while the island was under Turkish occupation.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] It worked on the ground floor of the island's city council building until 1902.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] Dr Stefanidis, its founder, called it «αστυχημείο», and its aim was the control of imported food as well as the local adulterations.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] In 1900, the first Greek Analytical Laboratory was founded at Chania, Crete.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] It was bombed and destroyed in 1941.The Chemistry Department of Athens University and the Chemical Engineering department of the National Technical University of Athens (Greek: Εθνικό Μετσόβιο Πολυτεχνείο, National Metsovian Polytechnic), sometimes known as Athens Polytechnic, were founded in 1918.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] Six years later, Zoe Mela (Macedonian fighter Pavlos Melas' daughter) wrote the Association of Greek Chemists' founding declaration together with nine more chemists on 31 March at her house (17 Asteriou street, Athens).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] It was then signed by 53 chemists from the Universities and the Rousopoulos Academy on 4 August 1924.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] Mrs Melpo Nikolitsa became the first woman elected into the Association's committee in 1953.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] In January 1960, all the chemists-applicants for employment as chemistry secondary education teachers are appointed by the Ministry of Education.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] The Association bought its own office on 14 June 1963, where the headquarters remain until today.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] Registration in the Association of Greek Chemists is obligatory according to the Law 1804/1988 for those who meet the requirements.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] Members can be those that possess a university degree in chemistry or its equivalent.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] The equivalency to a University chemistry degree is recognized by a special body (DIKATSA) set up by the Ministry of Education.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] Those obliged to become members fill in an application form, submit a copy of their University degree or its equivalent and pay the membership fees.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] The current annual membership fee is 35 euros.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] One of the benefits of membership is the receipt of the Association's flagship publication, the chimika chronika (chemical chronicles) magazine.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] It was published by the AGC from 1936 until 1997.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] The magazine has changed its name twice in the past: Chimika Chronika (1936-1968), Chimika Chronika Epistemonike Ekdosis (1969-1970), and Chimika Chronika New Series (1972-1997).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] The Association's website is used to announce available funding by government or private bodies.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/association-of-greek-chemists] The AGC is affiliated with a number of professional bodies, such as the Panhellenic Association of Industrial Chemists, the Panhellenic Association of Shipping Chemists, and the Association of employees of the General Chemistry Laboratory.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/belgian-society-of-biochemistry-and-molecular-biology] The **Belgian Society of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology** (**BMB**) is a Belgian non-profit organization, concerned with biochemistry and molecular biology.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/belgian-society-of-biochemistry-and-molecular-biology] The BMB was created, based on an initiative of Marcel Florkin, so a Belgian society could join the new International Union of Biochemistry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/belgian-society-of-biochemistry-and-molecular-biology] The first charter of the society was drafted by Edouard J.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/belgian-society-of-biochemistry-and-molecular-biology] Bigwood, Jean Brachet, Christian de Duve, Marcel Florkin, Lucien Massart, Paul Putzeys, Laurent Vandendriessche and Claude Lièbecq.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/belgian-society-of-biochemistry-and-molecular-biology] The first general assembly was held on 12 January 1952, and the first President of the society was Marcel Florkin, with Claude Lièbecq as secretary and treasurer.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/british-mass-spectrometry-society] The **British Mass Spectrometry Society** is a registered charity founded in 1964 that encourages participation in every aspect of mass spectrometry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/british-mass-spectrometry-society] It aims to encourage participation in all aspects of mass spectrometry on the widest basis, to promote knowledge and advancement in the field and to provide a forum for the exchange of views and information.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/british-mass-spectrometry-society] The first foundations of the BMSS were laid in 1949 with the establishment of the Mass Spectrometry Panel by the Hydrocarbon Research Group.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/british-mass-spectrometry-society] The society's annual meeting is held in the first week of September as well as regular special interest group meetings (Lipidomics, MALDI & Imaging, Ambient Ionisation, Environmental & Food Analysis) through the year, in locations throughout the United Kingdom.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/british-mass-spectrometry-society] In 1985, the Society used the proceeds from the 10th International Mass Spectrometry Conference to establish 7 Beynon PhD Studentships.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/british-mass-spectrometry-society] In 2007, the Society announced they would initiate summer studentship projects and in 2012 they announced BMSS research grants.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/british-mass-spectrometry-society] The management of the Society is vested in an Executive Committee made up of Officers and General Members, they also act as Trustees of the Society.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/british-mass-spectrometry-society] There are currently 10 officers of the Society namely the Chair, Vice-Chair, Treasurer, General Secretary, Meetings Secretary, Papers Secretary, Education Officer, Publicity Secretary, Special Interest Group Co-ordinator, and Digital Communications Officer.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/british-mass-spectrometry-society] The BMSS awards prizes to early career members during its annual meeting, named in honour of prominent past members.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Indigenous peoples have continuously inhabited what is now Canada for thousands of years.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Beginning in the 16th century, British and French expeditions explored and later settled along the Atlantic coast.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] As a consequence of various armed conflicts, France ceded nearly all of its colonies in North America in 1763.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 1867, with the union of three British North American colonies through Confederation, Canada was formed as a federal dominion of four provinces.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] This began an accretion of provinces and territories resulting in the displacement of Indigenous populations, and a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] This increased sovereignty was highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, and culminated in the *Canada Act 1982*, which severed the vestiges of legal dependence on the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is a parliamentary democracy and a constitutional monarchy in the Westminster tradition.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The country's head of government is the prime minister, who holds office by virtue of their ability to command the confidence of the elected House of Commons and is appointed by the governor general, representing the monarch of Canada, the ceremonial head of state.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The country is a Commonwealth realm and is officially bilingual (English and French) in the federal jurisdiction.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] It is very highly ranked in international measurements of government transparency, quality of life, economic competitiveness, innovation, education and human rights.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] It is one of the world's most ethnically diverse and multicultural nations, the product of large-scale immigration.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's long and complex relationship with the United States has had a significant impact on its history, economy, and culture.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] A developed country, Canada's advanced economy has a high nominal per capita GDP globally and ranks among the largest in the world by nominal GDP, relying chiefly upon its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade networks.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is recognized as a middle power; its support for multilateralism and internationalism has been closely related to its foreign policies of peacekeeping and aid for developing countries.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada promotes its domestically shared values through participation in multiple international organizations and forums.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] While a variety of theories have been postulated for the etymological origins of *Canada*, the name is now accepted as coming from the St.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Lawrence Iroquoian word *kanata*, meaning 'village' or 'settlement'.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 1535, Indigenous inhabitants of the present-day Quebec City region used the word to direct French explorer Jacques Cartier to the village of Stadacona.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Cartier later used the word *Canada* to refer not only to that particular village but to the entire area subject to Donnacona (the chief at Stadacona); by 1545, European books and maps had begun referring to this small region along the Saint Lawrence River as *Canada*.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] From the 16th to the early 18th century, *Canada* referred to the part of New France that lay along the Saint Lawrence River.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Following the British conquest of New France, this area was known as the British Province of Quebec from 1763 to 1791.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 1791, the area became two British colonies called Upper Canada and Lower Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] These two colonies were collectively referred to as the Canadas until their union as the Province of Canada in 1841.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Upon Confederation in 1867, *Canada* was adopted as the legal name for the new country at the London Conference and the word *dominion* was conferred as the country's title, reflecting its status as a self-governing nation within the British Empire.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Following the London Declaration of 1949, where it was agreed that India could be a full member of the Commonwealth as a republic, not a dominion, the leaders of the Commonwealth countries agreed that the other members of the Commonwealth should not continue to be referred to as *dominions*.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Laurent announced in the Canadian House of Commons that in light of the *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, and the changes to the Commonwealth, *dominion* was no longer an accurate term to use to refer to Canada and would no longer be used by the federal government.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Similarly, the United Kingdom no longer used the term *dominions* to refer to Canada or other members of the Commonwealth, instead beginning to use the term a *realm of the Commonwealth*.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The *Canada Act 1982*, which brought the Constitution of Canada fully under Canadian control, referred only to *Canada*.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Later that year, the name of the national holiday was changed from Dominion Day to Canada Day.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The first inhabitants of North America are generally hypothesized to have migrated from Siberia by way of the Bering land bridge and arrived at least 14,000 years ago.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Paleo-Indian archeological sites at Old Crow Flats and Bluefish Caves are two of the oldest sites of human habitation in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The characteristics of Indigenous societies included permanent settlements, agriculture, complex societal hierarchies, and trading networks.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Some of these cultures had collapsed by the time European explorers arrived in the late 15th and early 16th centuries and have only been discovered through archeological investigations.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Indigenous peoples in present-day Canada include the First Nations, Inuit, and Métis, the last being of mixed descent who originated in the mid-17th century when First Nations people married European settlers and their offspring subsequently developed their own identity.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Indigenous population at the time of the first European settlements is estimated to have been between 200,000 and two million, with a figure of 500,000 accepted by Canada's Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] As a consequence of European colonization, the Indigenous population declined by forty to eighty percent.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Although not without conflict, European Canadians' early interactions with First Nations and Inuit populations were relatively peaceful.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] First Nations and Métis peoples played a critical part in the development of European colonies in Canada, particularly for their role in assisting European coureurs des bois and voyageurs in their explorations of the continent during the North American fur trade.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] These early European interactions with First Nations would change from friendship and peace treaties to the dispossession of Indigenous lands through treaties.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] From the late 18th century, European Canadians forced Indigenous peoples to assimilate into a western Canadian society.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Settler colonialism reached a climax in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] A period of redress began with the formation of a reconciliation commission by the Government of Canada in 2008.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] This included acknowledgment of cultural genocide, settlement agreements, and betterment of racial discrimination issues, such as addressing the plight of missing and murdered Indigenous women.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] It is believed that the first documented European to explore the east coast of Canada was Norse explorer Leif Erikson.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In approximately 1000 AD, the Norse built a small short-lived encampment that was occupied sporadically for perhaps 20 years at L'Anse aux Meadows on the northern tip of Newfoundland.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] No further European exploration occurred until 1497, when seafarer John Cabot explored and claimed Canada's Atlantic coast in the name of Henry VII of England.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 1534, French explorer Jacques Cartier explored the Gulf of Saint Lawrence where, on July 24, he planted a 10-metre (33 ft) cross bearing the words, "long live the King of France", and took possession of the territory New France in the name of King Francis I.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The early 16th century saw European mariners with navigational techniques pioneered by the Basque and Portuguese establish seasonal whaling and fishing outposts along the Atlantic coast.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In general, early settlements during the Age of Discovery appear to have been short-lived due to a combination of the harsh climate, problems with navigating trade routes and competing outputs in Scandinavia.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 1583, Sir Humphrey Gilbert, by the royal prerogative of Queen Elizabeth I, founded St John's, Newfoundland, as the first North American English seasonal camp.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 1600, the French established their first seasonal trading post at Tadoussac along the Saint Lawrence.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] French explorer Samuel de Champlain arrived in 1603 and established the first permanent year-round European settlements at Port Royal (in 1605) and Quebec City (in 1608).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Among the colonists of New France, *Canadiens* extensively settled the Saint Lawrence River valley and Acadians settled the present-day Maritimes, while fur traders and Catholic missionaries explored the Great Lakes, Hudson Bay, and the Mississippi watershed to Louisiana.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Beaver Wars broke out in the mid-17th century over control of the North American fur trade.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The English established additional settlements in Newfoundland in 1610 along with settlements in the Thirteen Colonies to the south.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] A series of four wars erupted in colonial North America between 1689 and 1763; the later wars of the period constituted the North American theatre of the Seven Years' War.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Mainland Nova Scotia came under British rule with the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht and Canada and most of New France came under British rule in 1763 after the Seven Years' War.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Royal Proclamation of 1763 established First Nation treaty rights, created the Province of Quebec out of New France, and annexed Cape Breton Island to Nova Scotia.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] St John's Island (now Prince Edward Island) became a separate colony in 1769.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] To avert conflict in Quebec, the British Parliament passed the Quebec Act 1774, expanding Quebec's territory to the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] More importantly, the Quebec Act afforded Quebec special autonomy and rights of self-administration at a time when the Thirteen Colonies were increasingly agitating against British rule.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] It re-established the French language, Catholic faith, and French civil law there, staving off the growth of an independence movement in contrast to the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Proclamation and the Quebec Act in turn angered many residents of the Thirteen Colonies, further fuelling anti-British sentiment in the years prior to the American Revolution.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] After the American War of Independence, the 1783 Treaty of Paris recognized the independence of the United States and set the terms of peace, ceding British North American territories south of the Great Lakes and east of the Mississippi River to the new country.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The American war of independence also caused a large out-migration of Loyalists, the settlers who had fought against American independence.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Many moved to Canada, particularly Atlantic Canada, where their arrival changed the demographic distribution of the existing territories.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] New Brunswick was in turn split from Nova Scotia as part of a reorganization of Loyalist settlements in the Maritimes, which led to the incorporation of Saint John, New Brunswick, as Canada's first city.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] To accommodate the influx of English-speaking Loyalists in Central Canada, the Constitutional Act of 1791 divided the province of Canada into French-speaking Lower Canada (later Quebec) and English-speaking Upper Canada (later Ontario), granting each its own elected legislative assembly.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Canadas were the main front in the War of 1812 between the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Peace came in 1815; no boundaries were changed.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Immigration resumed at a higher level, with over 960,000 arrivals from Britain between 1815 and 1850.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] New arrivals included refugees escaping the Great Irish Famine as well as Gaelic-speaking Scots displaced by the Highland Clearances.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Infectious diseases killed between 25 and 33 percent of Europeans who immigrated to Canada before 1891.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The desire for responsible government resulted in the abortive Rebellions of 1837.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Durham Report subsequently recommended responsible government and the assimilation of French Canadians into English culture.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Act of Union 1840 merged the Canadas into a united Province of Canada and responsible government was established for all provinces of British North America east of Lake Superior by 1855.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The signing of the Oregon Treaty by Britain and the United States in 1846 ended the Oregon boundary dispute, extending the border westward along the 49th parallel.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] This paved the way for British colonies on Vancouver Island (1849) and in British Columbia (1858).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Anglo-Russian Treaty of Saint Petersburg (1825) established the border along the Pacific coast, but, even after the US Alaska Purchase of 1867, disputes continued about the exact demarcation of the Alaska–Yukon and Alaska–British Columbia border.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Following three constitutional conferences, the *British North America Act, 1867* officially proclaimed Canadian Confederation on July 1, 1867, initially with four provinces: Ontario, Quebec, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada assumed control of Rupert's Land and the North-Western Territory to form the Northwest Territories, where the Métis' grievances ignited the Red River Rebellion and the creation of the province of Manitoba in July 1870.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] British Columbia and Vancouver Island (which had been united in 1866) joined the confederation in 1871 on the promise of a transcontinental railway extending to Victoria in the province within 10 years, while Prince Edward Island joined in 1873.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 1898, during the Klondike Gold Rush in the Northwest Territories, Parliament created the Yukon Territory.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Alberta and Saskatchewan became provinces in 1905.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Between 1871 and 1896, almost one quarter of the Canadian population emigrated south to the US.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] To settle the West and attract European immigrants, Canada sponsored the construction of three transcontinental railways, enacted the *Dominion Lands Act* and founded the North-West Mounted Police to maintain regional authority.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] This period of westward expansion and nation building resulted in the displacement of many Indigenous peoples of the Canadian Prairies to "Indian reserves", clearing the way for ethnic European block settlements.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] This caused the collapse of the Plains Bison in western Canada and the introduction of European cattle farms and wheat fields dominating the land.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Indigenous peoples saw widespread famine and disease due to the loss of the bison and their traditional hunting lands.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The federal government did provide emergency relief, on condition of the Indigenous peoples moving to the reserves.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] During this time, Canada introduced the *Indian Act* extending its control over the First Nations to education, government and legal rights.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Because Britain still maintained control of Canada's foreign affairs under the British North America Act, 1867, its declaration of war in 1914 automatically brought Canada into the First World War.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Volunteers sent to the Western Front later became part of the Canadian Corps, which played a substantial role in the Battle of Vimy Ridge and other major engagements of the war.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Conscription Crisis of 1917 erupted when the Unionist Cabinet's proposal to augment the military's dwindling number of active members with conscription was met with vehement objections from French-speaking Quebecers.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 1919, Canada joined the League of Nations independently of Britain.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Great Depression in Canada during the early 1930s saw an economic downturn, leading to hardship across the country.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In response to the downturn, the Co-operative Commonwealth Federation (CCF) in Saskatchewan introduced many elements of a welfare state (as pioneered by Tommy Douglas) in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] On the advice of Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King, war with Germany was declared effective September 10, 1939, by King George VI, seven days after the United Kingdom.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The delay underscored Canada's independence.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The first Canadian Army units arrived in Britain in December 1939.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In all, over a million Canadians served in the armed forces during the Second World War.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canadian troops played important roles in many key battles of the war, including the failed 1942 Dieppe Raid, the Allied invasion of Italy, the Normandy landings, the Battle of Normandy, and the Battle of the Scheldt in 1944.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada provided asylum for the Dutch monarchy while that country was occupied and is credited by the Netherlands for major contributions to its liberation from Nazi Germany.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Despite another conscription crisis in Quebec in 1944, Canada finished the war with a large army and strong economy.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The financial crisis of the Great Depression led the Dominion of Newfoundland to relinquish responsible government in 1934 and become a Crown colony ruled by a British governor.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] After two referendums, Newfoundlanders voted to join Canada in 1949 as a province.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Socially democratic programs were also instituted, such as Medicare, the Canada Pension Plan, and Canada Student Loans; though, provincial governments, particularly Quebec and Alberta, opposed many of these as incursions into their jurisdictions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Finally, another series of constitutional conferences resulted in the *Canada Act 1982*, the patriation of Canada's constitution from the United Kingdom, concurrent with the creation of the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada had established complete sovereignty as an independent country under its own monarchy.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 1999, Nunavut became Canada's third territory after a series of negotiations with the federal government.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] At the same time, Quebec underwent profound social and economic changes through the Quiet Revolution of the 1960s, giving birth to a secular nationalist movement.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The radical Front de libération du Québec (FLQ) ignited the October Crisis with a series of bombings and kidnappings in 1970, and the sovereigntist Parti Québécois was elected in 1976, organizing an unsuccessful referendum on sovereignty-association in 1980.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Attempts to accommodate Quebec nationalism constitutionally through the Meech Lake Accord failed in 1990.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] This led to the formation of the Bloc Québécois in Quebec and the invigoration of the Reform Party of Canada in the West.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] A second referendum followed in 1995, in which sovereignty was rejected by a slimmer margin of 50.6 to 49.4 percent.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 1997, the Supreme Court ruled unilateral secession by a province would be unconstitutional, and the Clarity Act was passed by Parliament, outlining the terms of a negotiated departure from Confederation.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In addition to the issues of Quebec sovereignty, a number of crises shook Canadian society in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada joined the Gulf War in 1990 and was active in several peacekeeping missions in the 1990s, including operations in the Balkans during and after the Yugoslav Wars, and in Somalia, resulting in an incident that has been described as "the darkest era in the history of the Canadian military".
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] After the September 11 attacks in the United States, Canada sent troops to Afghanistan in 2001, resulting in the largest amount of Canadian deaths for any single military mission since the Korean War in the early 1950s.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 2011, Canadian forces participated in the NATO-led intervention into the Libyan Civil War and also became involved in battling the Islamic State insurgency in Iraq in the mid-2010s.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic in Canada began on January 27, 2020, causing widespread social and economic disruption.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 2021, possible gravesites of Indigenous children were found near former Canadian residential schools, highlighting the cultural genocide against Indigenous peoples.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] A trade war involving the United States began on February 1, 2025, when U.S. president Donald Trump signed orders imposing tariffs on goods entering the United States, alongside rhetoric suggesting the annexation of Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] By total area (including its waters), Canada is the second-largest country.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] By land area alone, Canada ranks fourth, due to having the world's largest area of fresh water lakes.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Stretching from the Atlantic Ocean in the east, along the Arctic Ocean to the north, and to the Pacific Ocean in the west, the country encompasses 9,984,670 square kilometres (3,855,100 sq mi) of territory.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is also home to the world's northernmost settlement, Canadian Forces Station Alert, on the northern tip of Ellesmere Island—latitude 82.5°N—which lies 817 kilometres (508 mi) from the North Pole.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In latitude, Canada's most northerly point of land is Cape Columbia in Nunavut at 83°6′41″N, with its southern extreme at Middle Island in Lake Erie at 41°40′53″N.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In longitude, Canada's land extends from Cape Spear, Newfoundland, at 52°37′W, to Mount St.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada can be divided into seven physiographic regions: the Canadian Shield, the Interior Plains, the Great Lakes–St.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Lawrence Lowlands, the Appalachian region, the Western Cordillera, Hudson Bay Lowlands, and the Arctic Archipelago.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Boreal forests prevail throughout the country, ice is prominent in northern Arctic regions and through the Rocky Mountains, and the relatively flat Canadian Prairies in the southwest facilitate productive agriculture.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Lawrence River (in the southeast) where the lowlands host much of Canada's economic output.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada has over 2,000,000 lakes—563 of which are larger than 100 square kilometres (39 sq mi)—containing much of the world's fresh water.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] There are also fresh-water glaciers in the Canadian Rockies, the Coast Mountains, and the Arctic Cordillera.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is geologically active, having many earthquakes and potentially active volcanoes.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Average winter and summer high temperatures across Canada vary from region to region.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Winters can be harsh in many parts of the country, particularly in the interior and Prairie provinces, which experience a continental climate, where daily average temperatures are near −15 °C (5 °F), but can drop below −40 °C (−40 °F) with severe wind chills.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In non-coastal regions, snow can cover the ground for almost six months of the year, while in parts of the north snow can persist year-round.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Coastal British Columbia has a temperate climate, with a mild and rainy winter.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] On the east and west coasts, average high temperatures are generally in the low 20s °C (70s °F), while between the coasts, the average summer high temperature ranges from 25 to 30 °C (77 to 86 °F), with temperatures in some interior locations occasionally exceeding 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Much of Northern Canada is covered by ice and permafrost.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The future of the permafrost is uncertain because the Arctic has been warming at three times the global average as a result of climate change in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's annual average temperature over land has risen by 1.7 °C (3.1 °F), with changes ranging from 1.1 to 2.3 °C (2.0 to 4.1 °F) in various regions, since 1948.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The rate of warming has been higher across the North and in the Prairies.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In the southern regions of Canada, air pollution from both Canada and the United States—caused by metal smelting, burning coal to power utilities, and vehicle emissions—has resulted in acid rain, which has severely impacted waterways, forest growth, and agricultural productivity.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is one of the largest greenhouse gas emitters globally, with emissions increased by 16.5 percent between 1990 and 2022.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is divided into 15 terrestrial and five marine ecozones.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] These ecozones encompass over 80,000 classified species of Canadian wildlife, with an equal number yet to be formally recognized or discovered.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Although Canada has a low percentage of endemic species compared to other countries, due to human activities, invasive species, and environmental issues in the country, there are currently more than 800 species at risk of being lost.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] About 65 percent of Canada's resident species are considered "Secure".
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Over half of Canada's landscape is intact and relatively free of human development.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The boreal forest of Canada is considered to be the largest intact forest on Earth, with approximately 3,000,000 square kilometres (1,200,000 sq mi) undisturbed by roads, cities or industry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Since the end of the last glacial period, Canada has consisted of eight distinct forest regions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Approximately 12.1 percent of the nation's landmass and freshwater are conservation areas, including 11.4 percent designated as protected areas.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Approximately 13.8 percent of its territorial waters are conserved, including 8.9 percent designated as protected areas.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's first National Park, Banff National Park was established in 1885.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's oldest provincial park, Algonquin Provincial Park was established in 1893.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Established in 2015, Lake Superior National Marine Conservation Area is the world's largest freshwater protected area.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's largest national wildlife region, established in 2018, is the Scott Islands Marine National Wildlife Area.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is described as a "full democracy", with a tradition of liberalism, and an egalitarian, moderate political ideology.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Since the 1960s, an emphasis on social justice has been a distinguishing element of Canada's political culture.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Peace, order, and good government, alongside an Implied Bill of Rights, are founding principles of Canadian federalism.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] At the federal level, Canada has been dominated by two relatively centrist parties practising "brokerage politics": the centre-left leaning Liberal Party of Canada and the centre-right leaning Conservative Party of Canada (or its predecessors).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The historically predominant Liberals position themselves at the centre of the political scale.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Far-right and far-left politics have never been a prominent force in Canadian society.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada has a parliamentary system within the context of a constitutional monarchy—the monarchy of Canada being the foundation of the executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The reigning monarch is also monarch of 14 other sovereign Commonwealth countries and Canada's 10 provinces.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The monarch appoints a representative, the governor general, on the advice of the prime minister, to carry out most of their ceremonial royal duties.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The monarchy is the source of sovereignty and authority in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] To ensure the stability of government, the governor general will usually appoint as prime minister the person who is the current leader of the political party that can obtain the confidence of a majority of members in the House.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The leader of the party with the second-most seats usually becomes the leader of the Official Opposition and is part of an adversarial parliamentary system intended to keep the government in check.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Parliament of Canada passes all federal statute laws.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] It comprises the monarch, the House of Commons, and the Senate.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] While Canada inherited the British concept of parliamentary supremacy, this was later, with the enactment of the Constitution Act, 1982, all but completely superseded by the American notion of the supremacy of the law.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Each of the 343 members of Parliament in the House of Commons is elected by simple plurality in an electoral district or riding.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The 105 members of the Senate, whose seats are apportioned on a regional basis, serve until age 75.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canadian federalism divides government responsibilities between the federal government and the 10 provinces.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Provincial legislatures are unicameral and operate in parliamentary fashion similar to the House of Commons.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's three territories also have legislatures, but these are not sovereign, have fewer constitutional responsibilities than the provinces, and differ structurally from their provincial counterparts.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Constitution of Canada is the supreme law of the country and consists of written text and unwritten conventions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The *Constitution Act, 1867* (known as the British North America Act, 1867 prior to 1982), affirmed governance based on parliamentary precedent and divided powers between the federal and provincial governments.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, granted full autonomy, and the *Constitution Act, 1982*, ended all legislative ties to Britain, as well as adding a constitutional amending formula and the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The *Charter* guarantees basic rights and freedoms that usually cannot be overridden by any government; a notwithstanding clause allows Parliament and the provincial legislatures to override certain sections of the *Charter* for a period of five years.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's judiciary interprets laws and has the power to strike down acts of Parliament that violate the constitution.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Supreme Court of Canada is the highest court, final arbiter, and has been led since 2017 by Richard Wagner, the Chief Justice of Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The governor general appoints the court's nine members on the advice of the prime minister and minister of justice.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The federal Cabinet also appoints justices to superior courts in the provincial and territorial jurisdictions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Common law prevails everywhere except Quebec, where civil law predominates.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Criminal law is solely a federal responsibility and is uniform throughout Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Law enforcement, including criminal courts, is officially a provincial responsibility, conducted by provincial and municipal police forces.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In most rural and some urban areas, policing responsibilities are contracted to the federal Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canadian Aboriginal law provides certain constitutionally recognized rights to land and traditional practices for Indigenous groups in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Various treaties and case laws were established to mediate relations between Europeans and many Indigenous peoples.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The role of Aboriginal law and the rights they support were reaffirmed by section 35 of the Constitution Act, 1982.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] These rights may include provision of services, such as healthcare through the Indian Health Transfer Policy, and exemption from taxation.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is a federation composed of 10 federated states, called provinces, and three federal territories.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] These may be grouped into four main regions: Western Canada, Central Canada, Atlantic Canada, and Northern Canada (*Eastern Canada* refers to Central Canada and Atlantic Canada together).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Provinces and territories have responsibility for social programs such as healthcare, education, and social programs, as well as administration of justice (but not criminal law).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Although the provinces collect more revenue than the federal government, equalization payments are made by the federal government to ensure reasonably uniform standards of services and taxation are kept between the richer and poorer provinces.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is recognized as a middle power for its role in global affairs with a tendency to pursue multilateral and international solutions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Globalization has significantly influenced Canadian foreign policies, with the country known for its promotion of peace and security through mediation, and for providing aid to developing countries.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada and the United States have a long and complex relationship; historically close allies, they co-operate regularly on military campaigns and humanitarian efforts.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada also maintains historic and traditional ties to the United Kingdom and to France, along with both countries' former colonies through its membership in the Commonwealth of Nations and the *Organisation internationale de la Francophonie*.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is noted for having a positive relationship with the Netherlands, owing, in part, to its contribution to the Dutch liberation during the Second World War.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada has diplomatic and consular offices in over 270 locations in approximately 180 foreign countries.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada promotes its domestically shared values through participating in multiple international organizations.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada was a founding member of the United Nations (UN) in 1945 and formed the North American Aerospace Defense Command together with the United States in 1958.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The country has membership in the World Trade Organization, the Five Eyes, the G7 and the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The country was a founding member of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum (APEC) in 1989 and joined the Organization of American States (OAS) in 1990.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada ratified the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) in 1948, and seven principal UN human rights conventions and covenants since then.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Alongside many domestic obligations, more than 3,000 Canadian Armed Forces (CAF) personnel are deployed in multiple foreign military operations.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Canadian unified forces comprise the Royal Canadian Navy, Canadian Army, and Royal Canadian Air Force.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The nation employs a professional, volunteer force of approximately 68,000 active personnel and 27,000 reserve personnel.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In March 2026, Canada achieved the NATO target of spending 2% of its GDP on defence for the 2026 fiscal year.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] This marks a significant increase from previous years—roughly 1.3% to 1.4% between 2021 and 2024.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's role in developing *peacekeeping* and its participation in initiatives during the 20th century has played a major role in its positive global image.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Peacekeeping is deeply embedded in Canadian culture and a distinguishing feature that Canadians feel sets their foreign policy apart from the United States.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada has long been reluctant to participate in military interventions that are not sanctioned by the United Nations, such as the Vietnam War, the 2003 invasion of Iraq and 2026 Iran war.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Since the 21st century, Canadian direct participation in UN peacekeeping efforts has greatly declined.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The large decrease was a result of Canada directing its participation to UN-sanctioned military operations through the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, rather than directly through the UN.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The change to participation via NATO has resulted in a shift towards more militarized and deadly missions rather than traditional peacekeeping duties.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's mixed-market economy is highly developed, ranking as the world's ninth-largest by nominal GDP as of 2023, at approximately US$2.221 trillion.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The country is one of the world's largest trading nations, with a highly globalized economy.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 2021, Canadian trade in goods and services reached $2.016 trillion.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's exports totalled over $637 billion, while its imported goods were worth over $631 billion, of which approximately $391 billion originated from the United States.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 2018, Canada had a trade deficit in goods of $22 billion and a trade deficit in services of $25 billion.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Toronto Stock Exchange is the ninth-largest stock exchange in the world by market capitalization, listing over 1,500 companies with a combined market capitalization of over US$2 trillion.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Bank of Canada is the central bank of the country.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The minister of finance and minister of innovation, science, and industry use data from Statistics Canada to enable financial planning and develop economic policy.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada has a strong cooperative banking sector, with the world's highest per-capita membership in credit unions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] It ranks low in the Corruption Perceptions Index (14th in 2023) and "is widely regarded as among the least corrupt countries of the world".
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] It ranks high in the Global Competitiveness Report (19th in 2024).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's economy ranks above most Western nations on the Heritage Foundation's Index of Economic Freedom and experiences a relatively low level of income disparity.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The country's average household disposable income per capita is "well above" the OECD average.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada ranks among the lowest of the most developed countries for housing affordability and foreign direct investment.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The unemployment rate in 2025 was 6.8 percent.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Since the early 20th century, the growth of Canada's manufacturing, mining, and service sectors has transformed the nation from a largely rural economy to an urbanized, industrial one.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Canadian economy is dominated by the service industry, which employs about three-quarters of the country's workforce.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada has an unusually important primary sector, of which the forestry and petroleum industries are the most prominent components.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Many towns in northern Canada, where agriculture is difficult, are sustained by nearby mines or sources of timber.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's economic integration with the United States has increased significantly since the Second World War.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Canada – United States Free Trade Agreement (FTA) of 1988 eliminated tariffs between the two countries, while the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) expanded the free-trade zone to include Mexico in 1994 (later replaced by the Canada–United States–Mexico Agreement).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] As of 2023, Canada is a signatory to 15 free trade agreements with 51 different countries.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is one of the few developed nations that are net exporters of energy.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Atlantic Canada possess vast offshore deposits of natural gas, and Alberta hosts the fourth-largest oil reserves in the world.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The vast Athabasca oil sands and other oil reserves give Canada 13 percent of global oil reserves, constituting the world's third- or fourth-largest.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada is additionally one of the world's largest suppliers of agricultural products; the Canadian Prairies region is one of the most important global producers of wheat, canola, and other grains.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's main exports are zinc, uranium, gold, nickel, platinoids, aluminum, steel, iron ore, coking coal, lead, copper, molybdenum, cobalt, and cadmium.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada has a sizeable manufacturing sector centred in southern Ontario and Quebec, with automobiles and aeronautics representing particularly important industries.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The country's fishing and tourism industries are also a key contributor to the economy.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] In 2020, Canada spent approximately $41.9 billion on domestic research and development, with supplementary estimates for 2022 at $43.2 billion.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] As of 2023, the country has produced 15 Nobel laureates in physics, chemistry, and medicine.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The country ranks seventh in the worldwide share of articles published in scientific journals, according to the Nature Index, and is home to the headquarters of a number of global technology firms.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada has one of the highest levels of Internet access in the world, with approximately 95 percent of its population aged 15 and above.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada's achievements in science and technology include the creation of the modern alkaline battery, the discovery of insulin, the development of the polio vaccine, and discoveries about the interior structure of the atomic nucleus.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Other major Canadian scientific contributions include the artificial cardiac pacemaker, mapping the visual cortex, the development of the electron microscope, plate tectonics, deep learning, multi-touch technology, and the identification of the first black hole, Cygnus X-1.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada has a long history of discovery in genetics, which include stem cells, site-directed mutagenesis, T-cell receptor, and the identification of the genes that cause Fanconi anemia, cystic fibrosis, and early-onset Alzheimer's disease, among numerous other diseases.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] The Canadian Space Agency runs an active space program focused on deep-space, planetary, and aviation research, along with rockets and satellites.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada launched its first satellite, Alouette 1, in 1962.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] It contributes to the International Space Station and is known for its robotic tools, such as multiple Canadarms.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p01] Canada has initiated many long-term projects, including the Radarsat satellite series and the Black Brant rocket series.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The 2021 Canadian census enumerated a total population of 36,991,981, an increase of around 5.2 percent over the 2016 figure.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] It is estimated that Canada's population surpassed 40,000,000 in 2023.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The main drivers of population growth are immigration and, to a lesser extent, natural growth.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada has one of the highest per-capita immigration rates in the world, driven mainly by economic policy and family reunification.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] A record 483,390 immigrants were admitted in 2024.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada leads the world in refugee resettlement; it resettled more than 47,600 in 2022.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] New immigrants settle mostly in major urban areas, such as Toronto, Montreal, and Vancouver.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada's population density, at 4.2 inhabitants per square kilometre (11/sq mi), is among the lowest in the world, with approximately 95 percent of the population residing south of the 55th parallel north.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] About 80 percent of the population lives within 150 kilometres (93 mi) of the border with the contiguous United States.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada is highly urbanized, with over 80 percent of the population living in urban centres.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The majority of Canadians (over 70 percent) live below the 49th parallel, with 50 percent of Canadians living south of 45°42′ (45.7 degrees) north.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The most densely populated part of the country is the Quebec City–Windsor Corridor in Southern Quebec and Southern Ontario along the Great Lakes and the St.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The majority of Canadians (81.1 percent) live in family households, 12.1 percent report living alone, and 6.8 percent live with other relatives or unrelated persons.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Fifty-one percent of households are couples with or without children, 8.7 percent are single-parent households, 2.9 percent are multigenerational households, and 29.3 percent are single-person households.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Respondents in the 2021 Canadian census self-reported over 450 "ethnic or cultural origins".
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Over 60 percent of Canadians reported a single origin, and 36 percent reported having multiple ethnic origins, thus the overall total is greater than 100 percent.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Of the 36.3 million people enumerated in 2021, approximately 25.4 million reported being "White", representing 69.8 percent of the population.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The Indigenous population representing 5 percent or 1.8 million people, grew by 9.4 percent compared to the non-Indigenous population, which grew by 5.3 percent from 2016 to 2021.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Between 2011 and 2016, the visible minority population rose by 18.4 percent.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In 1961, about 300,000 people, less than two percent of Canada's population, were members of visible minority groups.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The 2021 census indicated that 8.3 million people, or almost one-quarter (23.0 percent) of the population, reported themselves as being or having been a landed immigrant or permanent resident in Canada—above the 1921 census previous record of 22.3 percent.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In 2021, India, China, and the Philippines were the top three countries of origin for immigrants moving to Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] A multitude of languages are used by Canadians, with English and French (the official languages) being the mother tongues of approximately 54 percent and 19 percent of Canadians, respectively.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada's official bilingualism policies give citizens the right to receive federal government services in either English or French with official-language minorities guaranteed their own schools in all provinces and territories.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Quebec's 1974 *Official Language Act* established French as the only official language of the province.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Although more than 82 percent of French-speaking Canadians live in Quebec, there are substantial Francophone populations in New Brunswick, Alberta, and Manitoba, with Ontario having the largest French-speaking population outside Quebec.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] New Brunswick, the only officially bilingual province, has an Acadian French minority constituting 33 percent of the population.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] There are also clusters of Acadians in southwestern Nova Scotia, on Cape Breton Island, and in central and western Prince Edward Island.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Other provinces have no official languages as such, but French is used as a language of instruction, in courts, and for other government services, in addition to English.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Manitoba, Ontario, and Quebec allow for both English and French to be spoken in the provincial legislatures and laws are enacted in both languages.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In Ontario, French has some legal status, but is not fully co-official.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] There are 11 Indigenous language groups, composed of more than 65 distinct languages and dialects.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Several Indigenous languages have official status in the Northwest Territories.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Inuktitut is the majority language in Nunavut and is one of three official languages in the territory.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] As of the 2021 census, just over 7.8 million Canadians listed a non-official language as their first language.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The country is also home to many sign languages, some of which are Indigenous.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] American Sign Language (ASL) is used across the country due to the prevalence of ASL in primary and secondary schools.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Quebec Sign Language (LSQ) is used primarily in Quebec.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada is religiously diverse, encompassing a wide range of beliefs and customs.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The Constitution of Canada refers to God; however, Canada has no official church and the government is officially committed to religious pluralism.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Freedom of religion in Canada is a constitutionally protected right.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Rates of religious adherence have steadily decreased since the 1970s.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] With Christianity in decline after having once been central and integral to Canadian culture and daily life, Canada has become a post-Christian, secular state.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Although the majority of Canadians consider religion to be unimportant in their daily lives, they still believe in God.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The practice of religion is generally considered a private matter.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] According to the 2021 census, Christianity is the largest religion in Canada, with Roman Catholics representing 29.9 percent of the population having the most adherents.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Christians overall representing 53.3 percent of the population, are followed by people reporting irreligion or having no religion at 34.6 percent.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Other faiths include Islam (4.9 percent), Hinduism (2.3 percent), Sikhism (2.1 percent), Buddhism (1.0 percent), Judaism (0.9 percent), and Indigenous spirituality (0.2 percent).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada has the second-largest national Sikh population, behind India.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Healthcare in Canada is delivered through the provincial and territorial systems of publicly funded health care, informally called Medicare.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] It is guided by the provisions of the *Canada Health Act* of 1984 and is universal.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Universal access to publicly funded health services "is often considered by Canadians as a fundamental value that ensures national healthcare insurance for everyone wherever they live in the country".
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Around 30 percent of Canadians' healthcare is paid for through the private sector.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] This mostly pays for services not covered or partially covered by Medicare, such as prescription drugs, dentistry and optometry.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Approximately 65 to 75 percent of Canadians have some form of supplementary health insurance; many receive it through their employers or access secondary social service programs.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Canada is experiencing an increase in healthcare expenditures due to a demographic shift toward an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In 2021, the average age in Canada was 41.9 years.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] A 2016 report by the chief public health officer found that 88 percent of Canadians, one of the highest proportions of the population among G7 countries, indicated that they "had good or very good health".
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Eighty percent of Canadian adults self-report having at least one major risk factor for chronic disease: smoking, physical inactivity, unhealthy eating or excessive alcohol use.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada has one of the highest rates of adult obesity among OECD countries, contributing to approximately 2.7 million cases of diabetes.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Four chronic diseases—cancer (leading cause of death), cardiovascular diseases, respiratory diseases, and diabetes—account for 65 percent of deaths in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] There are approximately 8 million people aged 15 and older with one or more disabilities in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In 2024, the Canadian Institute for Health Information estimated that healthcare spending reached $372 billion, or 12.4 percent of Canada's GDP for that year.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In 2022, Canada's per-capita spending on health expenditures ranked 12th among health-care systems in the OECD.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The Commonwealth Fund's 2021 report comparing the healthcare systems of the 11 most developed countries ranked Canada second-to-last.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Identified weaknesses were comparatively higher infant mortality rate, the prevalence of chronic conditions, long wait times, poor availability of after-hours care, and a lack of prescription drugs and dental coverage.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] An increasing problem in Canada's health system is a lack of healthcare professionals and hospital capacity.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Education in Canada is for the most part provided publicly, funded and overseen by federal, provincial, and local governments.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Education is within provincial jurisdiction and a province's curriculum is overseen by its government.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Education in Canada is generally divided into primary education, followed by secondary and post-secondary education.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Education in both English and French is available in most places across Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada has a large number of universities, almost all of which are publicly funded.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Established in 1663, Université Laval is the oldest post-secondary institution in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The nation's three top ranking universities are the University of Toronto, McGill, and the University of British Columbia.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The largest university is the University of Toronto, which has over 85,000 students.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] According to a 2022 report by the OECD, Canada is one of the most educated countries in the world; the country ranks first worldwide in the percentage of adults having tertiary education, with over 56 percent of Canadian adults having attained at least an undergraduate college or university degree.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada spends an average of 5.3 percent of its GDP on education.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The country invests heavily in tertiary education (more than US$20,000 per student).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] As of 2022, 89 percent of adults aged 25 to 64 have earned the equivalent of a high-school degree, compared to an OECD average of 75 percent.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada is influenced by British, French and Indigenous cultures and traditions.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] During the 20th century, Canadians with African, Caribbean, and Asian heritages have added to Canadian identity.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada's culture draws influences from its broad range of constituent nationalities, and policies that promote a just society are constitutionally protected.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Since the 1960s, Canada has emphasized human rights and inclusiveness for all its people.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadian identity shifted from primarily British-based to multicultural between the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The official state policy of multiculturalism is often cited as one of Canada's significant accomplishments and a key distinguishing element of Canadian identity.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In Quebec, cultural identity is strong and there is a French Canadian culture that is distinct from English Canadian culture.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] As a whole, Canada is in theory a cultural mosaic of regional ethnic subcultures with diverse areas and ethnic enclaves.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada's approach to governance emphasizing multiculturalism, which is based on selective immigration, social integration, and suppression of far-right politics, has wide public support.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadians also identify with the country's foreign aid policies, peacekeeping roles, the national park system, and the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Themes of nature, pioneers, trappers, and traders played an important part in the early development of Canadian symbolism.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Modern symbols emphasize the country's geography, northern climate, lifestyles, and the Canadianization of traditional European and Indigenous symbols.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The use of the maple leaf as a symbol dates to the early 18th century in New France.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The maple leaf is depicted on Canada's current and previous flags and on the arms of Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada's official tartan, known as the "maple leaf tartan", reflects the colours of the maple leaf through the seasons—green in the spring, gold in the early autumn, red at the first frost, and brown after falling.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The arms of Canada are closely modelled after those of the United Kingdom, with French and distinctive Canadian elements replacing or added to those derived from the British version.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadian cuisine items such as Canadian beer, maple syrup, Nanaimo bars, butter tarts, and the Quebec dishes of poutine and tourtière, alongside material items such as tuques, canoes and Hudson's Bay point blanket are considered as uniquely Canadian.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadian coins feature many of these symbols: the loon on the $1 coin, the coat of arms on the 50¢ piece, and the beaver on the nickel.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] An image of the monarch appears on $20 bank notes and the obverse of coins.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadian literature is often divided into French- and English-language literatures, which are rooted in the literary traditions of France and Britain, respectively.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The earliest Canadian narratives were of travel and exploration.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] This developed into three major themes of historical Canadian literature: nature, frontier life, and Canada's position within the world, all of which tie into the garrison mentality.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The evolution of Canadian literature is intricately linked to the country's historical and social contexts, often mirroring the challenges and changes in Canadian society.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] As Canadian literature progressed into the 20th and 21st centuries, it began to address a broader array of subjects and themes, such as women's rights, LGBTQ rights, immigrant experiences, environmental issues, the relationship with Indigenous peoples, and Canadian values and identity.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Financial support from governmental bodies, such as the Canada Council for the Arts and various provincial grant programs, facilitates the creation, publication, and promotion of works by Canadian authors.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Numerous Canadian authors have received international literary awards including the Nobel Prize in Literature, the Booker Prize, and the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadian literary awards and prizes include the Governor General's Literary Awards, the Giller Prize, the Latner Griffin Writers' Trust Poetry Prize, the Burt Award for First Nations, Inuit and Métis Literature and several accolades for literature aimed at children.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Art in Canada is marked by thousands of years of habitation by Indigenous peoples, and, in later times, artists have combined British, French, Indigenous, and American artistic traditions, at times embracing European styles while working to promote nationalism.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The nature of Canadian art reflects these diverse origins, as artists have taken their traditions and adapted these influences to reflect the reality of their lives in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The Group of Seven is often considered the first uniquely Canadian artistic group and style of painting.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Inuit art since the 1950s has been the traditional gift given to foreign dignitaries by the Canadian government.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Historically, the Catholic Church was the primary patron of art in early Canada, especially Quebec.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The Government of Canada has played a role in the development of art, through the department of Canadian Heritage by giving grants to art galleries, as well as by establishing and funding art schools and colleges across the country, and through the Canada Council for the Arts.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The Canada Council Art Bank also helps artists by buying and publicizing their work.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Great achievements in art in Canada are recognized through various awards and prizes, such as the Molson Prize, the Audain Prize for the Visual Arts, and the Governor General's Visual and Media Arts Awards.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadian music reflects a variety of regional scenes.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada has developed a vast music infrastructure that includes church halls, chamber halls, conservatories, academies, performing arts centres, record companies, radio stations, music charts, and television music video channels.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Government support programs, such as the Canada Music Fund, assist a wide range of musicians and entrepreneurs who create, produce and market original and diverse Canadian music.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] As a result of its cultural importance, as well as government initiatives and regulations, the Canadian music industry is one of the largest in the world, producing internationally renowned composers, musicians, and ensembles.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Achievements in music are recognized through various awards and prizes, most notably, the Juno Awards presented by the Canadian Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The country also hosts numerous music halls of fame with the Canadian Music Hall of Fame honouring musicians at the national level for their lifetime achievements.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] "God Save the King" has been used in Canada since the late 1700s and is the country's de facto royal anthem.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Patriotic music by Canadians dates back over 200 years, with "The Bold Canadian", written in 1812, popular throughout the 19th century.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] "The Maple Leaf Forever", written in 1866, was popular and served as an unofficial national anthem of English Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] "O Canada", originally composed in French in 1880, also served as an unofficial national anthem during the 20th century and was adopted as the country's official anthem in 1980.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada's media is highly autonomous, diverse, and very regionalized.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The *Broadcasting Act* declares "the system should serve to safeguard, enrich, and strengthen the cultural, political, social, and economic fabric of Canada".
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada has a well-developed media sector, but its cultural output—particularly in English films, television shows, and magazines—is often overshadowed by imports from the United States.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] As a result, the preservation of a distinctly Canadian culture is supported by federal government programs, laws, and institutions such as the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC), the National Film Board of Canada (NFB), and the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadian mass media, both print and digital, and in both official languages, is largely dominated by a "handful of corporations".
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The largest of these corporations is the country's national public broadcaster, the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation, which also plays a significant role in producing domestic cultural content, operating its own radio and TV networks in both English and French.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In addition to the CBC, some provincial governments offer their own public educational TV broadcast services as well, such as TVOntario and Télé-Québec.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Non-news media content in Canada, including film and television, is influenced both by local creators as well as by imports from the United States, the United Kingdom, Australia, and France.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In an effort to reduce the amount of foreign-made media, government interventions in television broadcasting can include both regulation of content and public financing.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadian tax laws limit foreign competition in magazine advertising.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada's official national sports are ice hockey and lacrosse.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Other major professional games include curling, basketball, baseball, soccer, and football.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Great achievements in Canadian sports are recognized by numerous "Halls of Fame" and museums, such as Canada's Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canada shares several major professional sports leagues with the United States.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadian teams in these leagues include seven franchises in the National Hockey League, three Major League Soccer teams, and one team in each of Major League Baseball and the National Basketball Association.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Other popular professional competitions include the Canadian Football League, National Lacrosse League, the Canadian Premier League, and the curling tournaments hosted by Curling Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Canadians identified hockey as their preferred sport for viewing, followed by soccer and then basketball.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] In terms of participation, swimming was the most commonly reported sport by over one-third (35 percent) of Canadians in 2023.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] This was closely followed by cycling (33 percent) and running (27 percent).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] Sports such as golf, volleyball, badminton, bowling, and martial arts are also widely enjoyed at the youth and amateur levels.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canada-p02] The country co-hosted the 2026 FIFA World Cup alongside Mexico and the United States.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The **Canadian Society for Mass Spectrometry** is an organization that promotes mass spectrometry in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The goal of the society is to stimulate interest and collaborations in the Canadian mass spectrometry community.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The society organizes conferences, awards prices and runs an online job board.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry] The society is an affiliate society of the International Mass Spectrometry Foundation.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] The **Canadian Society of Clinical Chemists** (**CSCC**) is a nonprofit scientific society that represents clinical chemists (also known as clinical biochemists) in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] The organization aims to advance the practice of clinical chemistry in Canada through the promotion of importance in education, research, and practice, working at the international, national, provincial, and local levels.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] The CSCC is a full member of the International Federation of Clinical Chemistry and Laboratory Medicine (IFCC), which is associated with the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC).
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] In Canada, clinical chemists work as members of the medical laboratory management team, which consists of pathologists, laboratory managers, and senior technologists.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] They are primarily responsible for setting the standards of performance for the clinical biochemistry laboratory.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] The knowledge they acquired from post doctoral training programs is applied to maintain efficiency in the lab.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] The founding meeting for the CSCC was held in Montreal, Quebec on October 17, 1956.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] Since that time, the membership has grown to several hundred clinical chemists.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] In 1986 the Canadian Academy of Clinical Biochemistry was established as the academic body of the CSCC to oversee training, certification, accreditation, and professional development of clinical chemists in Canada.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] A syllabus for post doctoral training in clinical biochemistry was developed and is maintained by the CACB as a guide to program directors and trainees.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] The CSCC holds an Annual Scientific Congress and Annual General Meeting.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] The 61st annual CSCC conference was held in San Diego, CA, USA from July 31-August 4, 2017 as a joint meeting with the AACC.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] The CSCC monitors the quality of testing services and acts as technical experts to evaluate and select methods and instrumentation.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] They apply their clinical and technical knowledge to assist physicians in selecting and interpreting tests, as well as supporting the laboratory's research and teaching activities.
[src:canadian-society-for-mass-spectrometry/canadian-society-of-clinical-chemists] The society also produces publications, including the scientific journal *Clinical Biochemistry*, a member newsletter *CSCC News*, and position papers on current issues such as cardiac troponin testing.
